    {
        "content": "<p>If you unfold the definitions, then you're trying to show that if a sequence of (bounded) continuous functions <code>f n</code> converges to <code>g</code> pointwise on <code>[a, b]</code>, then it converges to <code>g</code> uniformly on <code>[a, b]</code>. Consider the sequence <code>f n</code> equal to <code>nx</code> on <code>[0, 1/n]</code>, then <code>2-nx</code> on <code>[1/n, 2/n]</code>, then <code>0</code>. It converges to zero pointwise, but not uniformly.</p>",
        "id": 515998404,
        "sender_full_name": "Yury G. Kudryashov",
        "timestamp": 1746340055
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Hi, thanks! I thought <code>Tendsto (fun n ‚Ü¶ (f n).toFun) atTop (ùìù g.toFun)</code> means the <em>uniform</em> convergence, in the sense of L‚àû norm‚Ä¶<br>\nSorry I am new to Lean. Could you explain how to unfold definitions? I have tried <code>#check</code> and <code>dsimp [Tendsto] at h</code>, but they do not tell which metric is being used.</p>",
        "id": 515998701,
